06517nam a22009495i 9781512824360DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815128243607 a10.9783/97815128243602doi  a(DE-B1597)651285  a(OCoLC)1376195750  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBM526 7aSOC0490002bisacsh04a296.1/609223/eng/202304171 aSchulte, Christoph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aZimzum :bGod and the Origin of the World /cChristoph Schulte. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (424 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the English Edition -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Origins in the Holy Land -- tChapter 2. From Esoteric to Exoteric: European Kabbalists Transmitting Texts and Ideas in the First Half of the Seventeenth Century -- tChapter 3. Christians Unveil the Kabbalah in the Seventeenth and Eighteenth Centuries -- tChapter 4. Shabbateans and Anti-Shabbateans -- tChapter 5. The Origins of Chassidism -- tChapter 6. God’s Contraction in German Idealism and Romanticism -- tChapter 7. The Haskalah and Wissenschaft des Judentums -- tChapter 8. Zimzum in the Twentieth Century -- tConclusion. The Anthropology of Zimzum -- tAppendix A. Sources on Zimzum: Texts, Art, and Music -- tAppendix B. Four Hundred Fifty Years of Zimzum Diffusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Hebrew word zimzum originally means “contraction,” “withdrawal,” “retreat,” “limitation,” and “concentration.” In Kabbalah, zimzum is a term for God’s self-limitation, done before creating the world to create the world. Jewish mystic Isaac Luria coined this term in Galilee in the sixteenth century, positing that the God who was “Ein-Sof,” unlimited and omnipresent before creation, must concentrate himself in the zimzum and withdraw in order to make room for the creation of the world in God’s own center. At the same time, God also limits his infinite omnipotence to allow the finite world to arise. Without the zimzum there is no creation, making zimzum one of the basic concepts of Judaism.The Lurianic doctrine of the zimzum has been considered an intellectual showpiece of the Kabbalah and of Jewish philosophy. The teaching of the zimzum has appeared in the Kabbalistic literature across Central and Eastern Europe, perhaps most famously in Hasidic literature up to the present day and in philosopher and historian Gershom Scholem’s epoch-making research on Jewish mysticism. The Zimzum has fascinated Jewish and Christian theologians, philosophers, and writers like no other Kabbalistic teaching. This can be seen across the philosophy and cultural history of the twentieth century as it gained prominence among such diverse authors and artists as Franz Rosenzweig, Hans Jonas, Isaac Bashevis Singer, Harold Bloom, Barnett Newman, and Anselm Kiefer.This book follows the traces of the zimzum across the Jewish and Christian intellectual history of Europe and North America over more than four centuries, where Judaism and Christianity, theosophy and philosophy, divine and human, mysticism and literature, Kabbalah and the arts encounter, mix, and cross-fertilize the interpretations and appropriations of this doctrine of God’s self-entanglement and limitation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCabalaxHistory. 0aGod (Christianity). 0aGod (Judaism). 0aHasidism. 0aIntellectual lifexReligious aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aChristian Hebraists.  aChristian Kabbalah.  aCorey L. Twitchel